            "fact_heading": "Facts",
            "fact_text": "<p>Same Sparkle, Same BrillianceThere’s a common misconception that lab grown diamonds are not “real” diamonds. This is far from true. Not only are lab grown and mined natural diamonds physically and visually identical, they are also chemically the same. They’re made up of pure carbon molecules arranged in a crystal structure known as the cubic lattice. This is the structure that gives diamonds their hardness and durability, giving them a rating of 10 on the Mohs scale. While the two diamonds have different origins, they are chemically the same. Meaning, all other properties are the same as well, for example, these lab grown gems carry the same refractive index, durability, and brilliance as their natural counterparts.Lab grown diamonds undergo the same crystallization process as natural diamonds except under controlled conditions and shorter timelines. Due to lab grown diamonds being the same chemically as their mined counterparts, even trained gemologists can not differentiate between the two without specialised lab equipment. That’s not it! Lab grown and natural diamonds are not only graded and certified by the same bodies that grade and certify mined diamonds, such as GIA and IGI, they are also evaluated and priced on the same parameters as the mined diamonds, i.e., cut, color, clarity, and carat weight.</p>"
